What about the width?

00:13:06.765 --> 00:13:08.880
Well, for the width,

00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:12.750
you can go basically any width you want.

00:13:12.750 --> 00:13:18.120
But what I'd like to do is I like to use a 16 by 9 ratio.

00:13:18.120 --> 00:13:21.465
I have a cool little plugin for that.

00:13:21.465 --> 00:13:24.360
It's called Aspects.

00:13:24.360 --> 00:13:30.600
You can find this in the Figma plugins directory.

00:13:30.600 --> 00:13:34.080
Just search for aspects and you'll find it.

00:13:34.080 --> 00:13:37.260
This allows me to select an element,

00:13:37.260 --> 00:13:40.170
choose an aspect ratio,

00:13:40.170 --> 00:13:45.195
and choose a property to resize based on that aspect ratio.

00:13:45.195 --> 00:13:47.970
In my case, I want to change the width because

00:13:47.970 --> 00:13:51.060
the height is set at it's correct dimensions.

00:13:51.060 --> 00:13:59.055
I'm going to hit apply and this changed the width to 427 pixels.

00:13:59.055 --> 00:14:06.405
Now I have a perfectly sized shape for a 16 by 9 ratio.

00:14:06.405 --> 00:14:14.835
With the selected, what I can do now is click it and under Fill,

00:14:14.835 --> 00:14:18.210
select "Image", choose "Image".

00:14:18.210 --> 00:14:21.240
I can open my landing page starter kit,

00:14:21.240 --> 00:14:29.895
go to Placeholder images and I can choose any of the images from this UI kit.

00:14:29.895 --> 00:14:36.480
Let's choose "Main". Here you have several options for how the image behaves.

00:14:36.480 --> 00:14:38.040
You can choose between Fill,

00:14:38.040 --> 00:14:40.605
Fit, Crop, and Tile.

00:14:40.605 --> 00:14:43.575
In my case, I'm just going to leave it on Fill.

00:14:43.575 --> 00:14:51.690
Then I'm going to select this and I'm going to add a drop shadow. Like so.

00:14:51.690 --> 00:14:57.570
Now what I want to do is create a nice grid out of these images.

00:14:57.570 --> 00:15:00.540
I'm going to select "Duplicate" and I'm going to position

00:15:00.540 --> 00:15:03.975
this at 32 pixels from the other one.

00:15:03.975 --> 00:15:07.200
Let's duplicate again, 32 pixels.

00:15:07.200 --> 00:15:12.350
Let's do that again.

00:15:12.350 --> 00:15:15.540
Let's do that again.

00:15:15.540 --> 00:15:22.665
Let's do a third column. Like so.

00:15:22.665 --> 00:15:28.530
Now, let's go ahead and add some fresh images here.

00:15:28.530 --> 00:15:31.800
Actually to make it more interesting, here's what we'll do,

00:15:31.800 --> 00:15:36.670
we'll delete the top images here.

00:15:38.300 --> 00:15:45.730
We're going to move these up like so.

00:15:47.670 --> 00:15:52.885
It just adds a little bit of a more visual interest.

00:15:52.885 --> 00:15:55.405
Let's change the images now.

00:15:55.405 --> 00:16:00.490
When you have a rectangle shape with an image fill,

00:16:00.490 --> 00:16:05.785
you can actually double-click it to open up the fill dialogue.

00:16:05.785 --> 00:16:07.780
So let's choose another image,

00:16:07.780 --> 00:16:14.060
maybe this one and let's do the same for the rest.

00:16:24.240 --> 00:16:28.345
All right, so once you're happy with the result, here's what you do.

00:16:28.345 --> 00:16:32.590
You select all of these and you go right here where

00:16:32.590 --> 00:16:37.300
it says components and select create component.

